    "file_name": "Local_Avian_Impact_Study_vFinal.pdf",
    "executive_summary": "The proposed site for the Aegis Coastal Campus is situated directly on the Atlantic Flyway, a major migratory route for over 200 species of birds. The project's proximity to the coastline significantly increases the risk of high-frequency bird strike events.",
    "key_findings": [
      "Total estimated annual strikes with non-mitigated mirror glass (Option A): 3,200 - 4,800 deaths per year.",
      "Most affected species: Songbirds (82%), Shorebirds (15%), Threatened species (3%).",
      "Option B (Fritted/Patterned) is projected to reduce fatalities by 94%.",
      "Local ordinances (Coastal Protection Act, Section 12-B) mandate 'Reasonable and Best Efforts' to mitigate wildlife mortality. Failure to comply can result in fines up to $1,000 per documented strike."
    ],
    "mitigation_recommendations": "It is strongly recommended that a visual marker density of 2x2 inches (Option B) be utilized for all exterior glazing. If non-mitigated glass is used, retrofitting with UV-reflective films or netting will likely be required post-construction at an estimated cost of $2.2M, plus legal liabilities."
  }
}
